\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Categorical State Resolution of Gibbs' Paradox.} \textbf  {(Left)} Traditional view: Mixing identical gases produces no entropy change (paradox). \textbf  {(Center)} Categorical mechanics: Each physical configuration occupies unique categorical position $C_i$ in completion sequence. Initial state at $C_{\text  {initial}}$, mixed state explores new categorical positions $C_{\text  {new}}$, re-separated state cannot re-occupy $C_{\text  {initial}}$ (irreversibility) and must occupy $C_{\text  {final}}$ with higher entropy. \textbf  {(Right)} Entropy progression: $S(C_{\text  {initial}}) < S(C_{\text  {mixed}}) < S(C_{\text  {final}})$ despite identical spatial configurations at initial and final states. Red arrows indicate categorical progression (irreversible). Blue regions show available categorical state space shrinking as states are completed. This resolution enables single-molecule tracking despite quantum indistinguishability - foundation for 10$^{33}$× bandwidth enhancement in membrane interface.}}{8}{figure.caption.2}\protected@file@percent }
