\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {O$_2$ Molecular Geometry and Quantum State Encoding.} \textbf  {(A)} Molecular structure: O$_2$ bond length 1.21 Å, triplet ground state $^3\Sigma _g^-$ with two unpaired electrons (parallel spins) giving total spin $S=1$ and magnetic moment $\mu = 2\mu _B$. \textbf  {(B)} Vibrational ladder: Energy levels $E_\nu = \hbar \omega (\nu + 1/2)$ with ~25 accessible states at 300 K ($\omega \approx 1580$ cm$^{-1}$), encoding 5 bits. Red transitions show vibrational FRET to membrane lipids. \textbf  {(C)} Rotational manifold: $J = 0, 1, 2, ...$ with $E_J = BJ(J+1)$ where $B = 1.44$ cm$^{-1}$. Thermal population (300 K) spans $J = 0$-20, encoding 4 bits. Blue arrows indicate rotational-magnetic coupling. \textbf  {(D)} Spin triplet: Three magnetic substates $m_S = +1, 0, -1$ split by external magnetic field (Zeeman effect), encoding 2 bits. Green manifold shows coherent superposition states. \textbf  {(E)} Complete quantum identifier: $|\psi \rangle = |\nu , J, m_S\rangle $ provides 11-bit unique signature per molecule. \textbf  {(F)} Categorical encoding: Different categorical states $C_i$ map to different quantum state distributions $\{a_{\nu Jm}(C_i)\}$, creating distinguishable spectroscopic fingerprints despite quantum indistinguishability. This tri-level encoding (vibrational + rotational + spin) is foundation for molecular information carrier hypothesis.}}{22}{figure.caption.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:molecular_geometry}{{3}{22}{\textbf {O$_2$ Molecular Geometry and Quantum State Encoding.} \textbf {(A)} Molecular structure: O$_2$ bond length 1.21 Å, triplet ground state $^3\Sigma _g^-$ with two unpaired electrons (parallel spins) giving total spin $S=1$ and magnetic moment $\mu = 2\mu _B$. \textbf {(B)} Vibrational ladder: Energy levels $E_\nu = \hbar \omega (\nu + 1/2)$ with ~25 accessible states at 300 K ($\omega \approx 1580$ cm$^{-1}$), encoding 5 bits. Red transitions show vibrational FRET to membrane lipids. \textbf {(C)} Rotational manifold: $J = 0, 1, 2, ...$ with $E_J = BJ(J+1)$ where $B = 1.44$ cm$^{-1}$. Thermal population (300 K) spans $J = 0$-20, encoding 4 bits. Blue arrows indicate rotational-magnetic coupling. \textbf {(D)} Spin triplet: Three magnetic substates $m_S = +1, 0, -1$ split by external magnetic field (Zeeman effect), encoding 2 bits. Green manifold shows coherent superposition states. \textbf {(E)} Complete quantum identifier: $|\psi \rangle = |\nu , J, m_S\rangle $ provides 11-bit unique signature per molecule. \textbf {(F)} Categorical encoding: Different categorical states $C_i$ map to different quantum state distributions $\{a_{\nu Jm}(C_i)\}$, creating distinguishable spectroscopic fingerprints despite quantum indistinguishability. This tri-level encoding (vibrational + rotational + spin) is foundation for molecular information carrier hypothesis}{figure.caption.5}{}}
