\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Molecular Oscillatory Signature Encoding and BMD Recognition.} \textbf  {(A)} Frequency encoding: Each molecular species exhibits characteristic oscillatory frequency from rotational/vibrational modes. Lithium (Li$^+$): rigid-body rotation at 1.5 Hz; Citalopram: conformational oscillations at 0.8 Hz; Glucose: ring puckering at 180 Hz. Frequency spectrum quantized to ~$10^3$ distinguishable values → 10 bits information. \textbf  {(B)} Phase encoding: Temporal coordination within cardiac cycle (gray waveform). Molecules arriving at different phases $\phi $ (0-2π) encode timing information: 32 phase bins → 5 bits. Phase-locking to cardiac master clock enables synchronous sampling. \textbf  {(C)} Amplitude encoding: Concentration-dependent signal strength. Log-scale quantization provides ~8 distinguishable levels → 3 bits (pathway identity). \textbf  {(D)} Complete signature: $\mathcal  {S}(f, \phi , A)$ provides 18-20 bits per drug-BMD interaction. Color map shows S-entropy coordinate mapping: Knowledge ($S_K$, red), Time ($S_T$, blue), Entropy ($S_E$, green). \textbf  {(E)} BMD filtering: Recognition requires resonance matching $f_{\text  {match}} > 0.9$ (green region). In-resonance: >10× amplification, <100 ms recognition, 1 ATP cost. Out-of-resonance (red region): <2× amplification, >1 s, 3-5 ATP (inefficient). \textbf  {(F)} Recognition efficiency distribution: Mean $\langle f_{\text  {match}} \rangle = 72.1\%$ across therapeutic agents (histogram). This oscillatory encoding enables brain to distinguish thousands of molecular species via BMD equivalence - molecules mapped to tactile-equivalent patterns for instant recognition without learning.}}{26}{figure.caption.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:molecular_encodings}{{4}{26}{\textbf {Molecular Oscillatory Signature Encoding and BMD Recognition.} \textbf {(A)} Frequency encoding: Each molecular species exhibits characteristic oscillatory frequency from rotational/vibrational modes. Lithium (Li$^+$): rigid-body rotation at 1.5 Hz; Citalopram: conformational oscillations at 0.8 Hz; Glucose: ring puckering at 180 Hz. Frequency spectrum quantized to ~$10^3$ distinguishable values → 10 bits information. \textbf {(B)} Phase encoding: Temporal coordination within cardiac cycle (gray waveform). Molecules arriving at different phases $\phi $ (0-2π) encode timing information: 32 phase bins → 5 bits. Phase-locking to cardiac master clock enables synchronous sampling. \textbf {(C)} Amplitude encoding: Concentration-dependent signal strength. Log-scale quantization provides ~8 distinguishable levels → 3 bits (pathway identity). \textbf {(D)} Complete signature: $\mathcal {S}(f, \phi , A)$ provides 18-20 bits per drug-BMD interaction. Color map shows S-entropy coordinate mapping: Knowledge ($S_K$, red), Time ($S_T$, blue), Entropy ($S_E$, green). \textbf {(E)} BMD filtering: Recognition requires resonance matching $f_{\text {match}} > 0.9$ (green region). In-resonance: >10× amplification, <100 ms recognition, 1 ATP cost. Out-of-resonance (red region): <2× amplification, >1 s, 3-5 ATP (inefficient). \textbf {(F)} Recognition efficiency distribution: Mean $\langle f_{\text {match}} \rangle = 72.1\%$ across therapeutic agents (histogram). This oscillatory encoding enables brain to distinguish thousands of molecular species via BMD equivalence - molecules mapped to tactile-equivalent patterns for instant recognition without learning}{figure.caption.6}{}}
